Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees.

Drain @pineapple{4%ounce}(drained, juice reserved), reserving juice in a #medium bowl{} (you'll use the pineapple in the next step). Stir @Southwest Spice Blend{2%tablespoon}, @Tex-Mex Paste{1%unit}, @Tomato Paste{1.5%ounce}, and @water{2%tablespoon}(4 TBSP for 4 servings) into juice.

Drain and rinse @Black Beans{13.4%ounce}; add to bowl with spice mixture. Stir in @Pulled Pork{10%ounce}, breaking meat into smaller pieces with a #fork. Season generously with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Transfer pork and bean filling to #oven-ready aluminum tray{} (divide between both trays for 4).

Bake on middle rack until warmed through, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Meanwhile, wash and dry all produce.

Pick @cilantro{1/4%ounce}(leaves picked and torn) leaves from stems; tear leaves. Quarter @lime{1}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @pineapple{4%ounce}, torn cilantro, and juice from half the lime. Season with salt and pepper.

When pork and bean filling has 5 minutes left in the oven, wrap @flour tortillas{6} in #aluminum foil{}.

Transfer to oven until warmed, ~{3-5%minutes}.

If pork and bean filling is not saucy enough, stir in another 1-2 TBSP water per tray.

Divide tortillas between plates; fill with as much pork and bean filling as you like. Top with @Sour Cream{4%tablespoon} and pineapple salsa. Serve with remaining lime wedges on the side.

> The week just isn't complete without a taco night. This version comes together in just 20 minutes,
> with minimal cleanup required thanks to handy oven-ready aluminum trays. Pile into warm tortillas
> with sour cream and a savory-sweet pineapple salsa for a truly spec-TACO-lar meal.